t, February 1944 We had rice gruel for lunch again. There was no tofu in it, but there were potatoes. We went through with the closing ceremony and received our report cards. Everyone was there. From now on, I’ll persevere and not fail. —Manabe Ichiro, primary school student, July 1944 This collection of diaries gives readers a powerful, firsthand look at the effects of the Pacific War on eight ordinary Japanese. Immediate, vivid, and at times surprisingly frank, the diaries chronicle the last years of the war and its aftermath as experienced by a navy kamikaze pilot, an army straggler on Okinawa, an elderly Kyoto businessman, a Tokyo housewife, a young working woman in Tokyo, a teenage girl mobilized for war work, and two schoolchildren evacuated to the countryside. Samuel Yamashita’s introduction provides a helpful overview of the historiography on wartime Japan and offers valuable insights into the important, everyday issues that concerned Japanese during a different and disastrously difficult time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, Japanese. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xCampaignszJapan. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh1 aAiko, Takahashi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHisako, Yoshizawa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIchirō, Manabe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMihōko, Nakane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeiki, Nomura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShōko, Maeda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTsunejiro, Tamura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYasuo, Itabashi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel